mber 1247":"2 November 1247","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Charleton Fitz Adam, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Tutbury, Staffordshire, England":"Tutbury, Staffordshire, England","Charleton Fitz Adam, Somerset, , England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William FitzAdam II was born in 1195, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William FitzAdams, was 31 and his mother, Alice de Crèvecoeur, was 33. He married Margery DeQuarmby in 1220, in Somerset, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1252, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1195–1252":"1195–1252","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1223–1300":"1223–1300","1165–1206":"1165–1206","1163–1247":"1163–1247","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1163":"1163","1195":"1195","1282":"1282","1206":"1206","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","about 1206":"umbes 1206","1223":"1223","1300":"1300","about 1247":"umbes 1247","2 November 1247":"2. november 1247","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Hereford, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Charleton Fitz Adam, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Tutbury, Staffordshire, England":"Tutbury, Staffordshire, England","Charleton Fitz Adam, Somerset, , England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1195–1252":"1195–1252","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1223–1300":"1223–1300",